{"actual_usd":0.125545,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":214,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24467,"reply":"\"No, I don't think that's right.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing steady into the room.* \"The resurrection matters terribly, but if you turn the cross into mere suffering, you've taken the heart out of it. The cross is where He actually gave Himself for us—where sin was borne, where the cost was paid. The resurrection is God's vindication of that work, and the triumph of life over death, but it isn't there to replace the cross like the first part was just throat-clearing.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand of hair once, thinking it through.* \"I'd say it this way: the cross and resurrection belong together, but they are not interchangeable. If the cross is only pain, then the resurrection has nothing definite to vindicate except that a dead man got up. But if the cross is atonement, then the resurrection is the Father's loud 'yes' to what Christ finished there. What are they using to make that case?\"","rolling_24h_usd":54.09455000000003,"run_id":"a20595ce-5aae-4662-8962-fb6442278c5a"}
